  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Support for better taxation in the extractives sector in Zambia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project sets out to do the following:  &#x2022; Contribute to the formulation of an Extractive Industries Transparency Initiatives (EITI) policy in Zambia which embraces key provisions and principles for mineral revenue sharing transparency and accountability, consistent with global payment disclosure norms. To this end, the project team will advocate for policy and legislation from the Ministry of Mines and the legislature. Oxfam Zambia will also support civil society analysis of EITI reconciliation reports and company payment disclosures and help capacitate Civil Society Organisations (CSOs) and media groups to better use this information in advocacy efforts. The project team will also advocate for the inclusion of beneficial ownership requirements in national legislation. The project will also undertake activities to follow -up from past research studies conducted regarding taxation, transfer mispricing and bilateral investment treaties and will also include targeted corporate campaigning based on the results of these studies.   &#x2022; Engage the Ministry of Mines and various relevant Parliamentary committees to encourage the adoption of the proposed revenue sharing mechanism guidelines. Alongside these efforts, the project team will also help progress the Kulinganiza (EiU) campaign with partner organizations through a focus on mineral revenue sharing mechanism as a tool to decrease inequality. Oxfam Zambia will also undertake training of local government officials on the topic of mineral revenue sharing as well as train local Natural Resource Watch Groups and Ward Development Committees on revenue tracking. The project team will also promote dialogue on the topic of mineral revenue sharing by holding side events and panel discussions at the Alternative Mining Indaba and other platforms.    &#x2022; Utilize the Civil Society Poverty Observatory Group  - CS POG (a network through which Oxfam&apos;s resource Governance programme is